target: economy
validations:
  - name: money_updates
    type: agent_validation
    severity: error
    args:
      rubric: >
        Verify that the player's money balance updates each tick based on
        income and expenses. After placing an enclosure and buying animals,
        the balance should decrease. As visitors arrive and pay admission,
        the balance should increase. The HUD should display the current
        balance and it should change over time reflecting net income.
  - name: demand_curve
    type: agent_validation
    severity: error
    args:
      rubric: >
        Verify that the admission price affects visitor arrival rate. Set a
        low admission price and observe visitor arrival. Then set a high
        admission price and observe that fewer visitors arrive. The
        relationship should be inversely proportional — higher prices lead
        to fewer visitors. The effect should be visible in the visitor
        count over a period of time.
  - name: appeal_drives_visitors
    type: agent_validation
    severity: error
    args:
      rubric: >
        Verify that zoo appeal affects visitor rate. A zoo with more
        animals, more unique species, and happier animals should attract
        more visitors than an empty zoo. Adding a new animal or species
        should increase the arrival rate over time. The relationship should
        be noticeable when comparing a minimal zoo to a well-stocked one.
  - name: game_over_triggers
    type: agent_validation
    severity: error
    args:
      rubric: >
        Verify that the game ends when the zoo runs out of money with
        negative net income. Spend all money on enclosures and animals
        without building paths or attracting visitors, so expenses exceed
        revenue. When the balance reaches zero or below with negative
        income, a game-over screen should appear showing final stats. The
        simulation should stop updating.
